data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":387,"item_id":"msg_01ea7f233529bb07006918f8ceb40481978e0898f0e6fbc7c2","output_index":1,"content_index":0,"text":"A \"steam reactor\" is a non-technical way of referring to a nuclear reactor that produces steam from the heat generated by nuclear fission. That steam is then used to drive a turbine and generator to produce electricity.\n\nKey ideas — how it works\n- Nuclear fission in the reactor core releases heat.\n- That heat is transferred to water (or another coolant) and turns some or all of it into steam.\n- The steam powers a turbine connected to an electrical generator.\n- After the turbine, the steam is condensed back to water and returned to the system.\n\nTwo common ways reactors produce steam\n- Boiling Water Reactor (BWR): water in the reactor core boils directly and the produced steam goes to the turbine. Steam and radioactive particles can pass to the turbine building, so systems and shielding are designed for that.\n- Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR): water in the reactor is kept under high pressure so it does not boil. Heat is transferred via a heat exchanger (steam generator) to a secondary loop where water turns to steam. The turbine sees nonradioactive steam.\n\nMain components\n- Reactor core (fuel assemblies, moderator)\n- Control rods (to control or stop the chain reaction)\n- Coolant/heat-removal system\n- Steam generators or direct steam outlet (depending on design)\n- Turbine and generator\n- Condenser and feedwater system\n- Containment structure and safety systems\n\nSafety features (examples)\n- Control rods and automatic shutdown systems\n- Redundant cooling systems and emergency core cooling\n- Containment building to limit radioactive release\n- Multiple physical and procedural barriers\n\nIf you meant a different concept (for example, a chemical steam reformer or a reactor in a steam-chemical process), tell me and I’ll explain that instead. Do you want more detail on BWR vs PWR, safety, or how steam is conditioned for turbines?","logprobs":[]}

